Gradle, the script-based alternative.

Gradle is the other build tool you will constantly meet, and it takes a different philosophy from Maven. Instead of x-m-l, it uses a domain-specific language written in either Groovy or Kotlin, it runs noticeably faster on incremental builds because it aggressively caches and skips unchanged work, and it gives you full programmatic control over the build. It is also the tool that Spring Boot's own project generator, the initializr, defaults to today.

A Kotlin-D-S-L build file has a plugins block, where you apply things like the Spring Boot plugin, a java block where you can pin the language version through a toolchain, a repositories block pointing at Maven Central, and a dependencies block. Notice that the dependencies use the same group-colon-artifact coordinates as Maven, just written on one line, and that you distinguish normal dependencies, with implementation, from test-only ones, with test-implementation.

The common commands mirror Maven's. Gradlew build compiles, tests, and packages. Gradlew test runs the tests. Gradlew boot-run launches a Spring Boot application. And gradlew dependencies prints the dependency graph. That gradlew script is important: it is the Gradle wrapper, a tiny shim you commit alongside your project that automatically downloads the exact Gradle version the project expects. Maven has the same thing, called m-v-n-w. Always commit the wrapper, so no contributor needs the right version installed globally. To sum the two tools up in one line: Maven is simpler and more standard, Gradle is faster and more flexible. New Spring projects increasingly start with Gradle, while older codebases are almost always Maven.
